						Hereupon he made three little schedules. On one he wrote 'Ladder', on the
						second 'Rope', on the third 'Wings'. These he put in a hat, and each man
						must draw, and whatever he got, that was to be his. Those who got the ropes
						imagined themselves to have the best of it, but I chanced to get a ladder,
						which afflicted me greatly, for it was twelve feet long, and pretty
						weighty, and I was forced to carry it, whereas the others could handsomely
						coil their ropes about them. And as for the wings, the old man joined them
						so closely onto the third group, as if they had grown upon them.
					-
				-
					Chapter 6: Section 1: Paragraph 7
				-
