				Chapter 7: Section 6
			-
				-
					Chapter 7: Section 6: Paragraph 1
				-
					-
						At this last article we could not choose but laugh, and it may well have
						been placed after the rest only for a conceit. Now after vowing to them all
						by the King's sceptre, we were afterwards installed Knights with the usual
						ceremonies, and amongst other privileges set over Ignorance, Poverty, and
						Sickness, to handle them at our pleasure. And this was afterwards ratified
						in a little chapel (to which we were conducted in procession) and thanks
						returned to God for it. I also hung up there at that time my golden fleece
						and hat, and left them there for an eternal memorial, to the honour of God.
						And because everyone had to write his name there, I wrote thus:
					-
			-
				Chapter 7: Section 7
			-
				-
					Chapter 7: Section 7: Paragraph 1
				-
					-
						The highest wisdom is to know nothing.
					-
